  "prompt": "What type of motor is used in a ceiling fan? How does a ceiling fan work?",
  "response": "A ceiling fan typically uses an AC (alternating current) induction motor, specifically a single-phase induction motor. Here's how a ceiling fan works:\n\nMotor Components:\n1. Stator (stationary part)\n- Contains electrical windings\n- Generates a rotating magnetic field\n- Powered by household electrical current\n\n2. Rotor (rotating part)\n- Made of metal with copper or aluminum windings\n- Spins inside the stator's magnetic field\n- Attached to fan blades\n\nOperation:\n1. Electrical current enters the motor\n2. Stator windings create a rotating magnetic field\n3. The magnetic field induces current in the rotor\n4. Induced current creates another magnetic field\n5. Interaction between stator and rotor magnetic fields causes rotation\n6. Fan blades are attached to the rotor shaft\n7. Blade rotation creates airflow and cooling effect\n\nSpeed Control:\n- Achieved by varying electrical current through different winding configurations\n- Typically controlled by a pull chain or wall switch\n- Some modern fans use electronic speed controllers\n\nAdditional Features:\n- Capacitor for improved motor performance\n- Reversible rotation for winter/summer use\n- Energy-efficient designs\n\nThe motor converts electrical energy into mechanical rotational energy, enabling the fan to circulate air effectively.",
